note.body:
I will reply with documentation text:
> **Synchronously and immediately** updates the list of #WnckWindow on @screen. This bypasses the standard update mechanism, where the list of #WnckWindow is updated in the idle loop.
> 
> This is usually a bad idea for both performance and correctness reasons (**to get things right**, you need to write model-view **code that tracks changes**, not get a static list of open windows). However, this function can be useful for small applications that just do something and then exit.

So if possible you should listen to `window-opened` and `window-closed` signals. Or maybe `window-stacking-changed`...

Maybe in forced update case it could ignore inconsistent state... Documentation already mentions correctness as reason to avoid it, so it might be fine that `wnck_screen_get_windows` and `wnck_screen_get_windows_stacked` does not contain all / same windows.

It happens on startup indeed. This hint looks very promising indeed, thanks! But how should we deal with it? There are open windows, but it still gives a `NULL`... 

I'm wondering, why doesn't libwnck take care of waiting till a consistent state is reached and then returns the actual window list in this state instead of `NULL`?

Sorry, my bad, turned out, this was wrong. It is just the `get_windows_stacked` that makes trouble. The crash you mentioned here is also known, but we worked around it (a wnck screen is never initialized in a Wayland environment due to an `$XDG_SESSION_TYPE` check).

Wayland? There was regression:
https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/libwnck/-/issues/157

Fix is included in `43.1`. Otherwise that regression might be reason for crash (if your distro has not added patch).

Oh, sorry about that. Anyway `NULL` is valid return value! Code should deal with that.

https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/libwnck/-/blob/43.1/libwnck/screen.c#L1344-1368
Perhaps this is reason why it is `NULL` if that happens on startup.
If I'm not mistaken, this is already being done (line 4 in my original code snippet: `$wnck_screen->force_update if $wnck_screen;`). But the issue still persists.
Perhaps you should use `wnck_screen_force_update`?

> Function is documented to return list of windows or `NULL` if there is no windows on screen.

Apparently, `get_windows_stacked` sometimes returns NULL even if there are windows, and the screen is defined

I am currently in the process of getting some help with the debugging process. The first piece of new information is that actually not the function returns an undefined value, but the whole screen is undefined. I will add more information, as soon as there is some!
Thanks for your reply! I asked in our downstream bug report if any of the affected users is willing to create a stacktrace. I'll provide it as soon as I got one.

What do you mean with undefined? Can you attach stacktrace?

Function is documented to return list of windows or `NULL` if there is no windows on screen.

note.body:
When cache is invalidated `WnckWindow` and/or `WnckApplication` will emit icon changed signals. It does not really force to get new icon but if you use icons you do want to update them.

Also if you store icon somewhere without adding extra reference then after icon change signal stored icon will be invalid and must not be used.
